TY  - JOUR
T1  - Incentives for Efficient Inventory Management: The Role of Historical Cost
AU  - Baldenius, Tim
AU  - Reichelstein, Stefan
Y1  - 2005/07/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.1050.0360
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.1050.0360
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1032
EP  - 1045
VL  - 51
IS  - 7
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This paper examines inventory management from an incentive perspective. We show that when a manager has private information about future attainable revenues, the residual income performance measure based on historical cost can achieve optimal (second-best) incentives with regard to managerial effort as well as production and sales decisions. The LIFO (last-in?first-out) inventory flow rule is shown to be preferable to the FIFO (first-in?first-out) rule for the purpose of aligning incentives. Our analysis also finds support for the lower-of-cost-or-market inventory-valuation rule in situations where the manager receives new information after the initial contracting stage.
AB  - This paper examines inventory management from an incentive perspective. We show that when a manager has private information about future attainable revenues, the residual income performance measure based on historical cost can achieve optimal (second-best) incentives with regard to managerial effort as well as production and sales decisions. The LIFO (last-in?first-out) inventory flow rule is shown to be preferable to the FIFO (first-in?first-out) rule for the purpose of aligning incentives. Our analysis also finds support for the lower-of-cost-or-market inventory-valuation rule in situations where the manager receives new information after the initial contracting stage.
